        {
            "key": "research:counting numbers:1779066214:0",
            "value": "In mathematics, the natural numbers are the numbers 0, 1, 2, 3, and so on, possibly excluding 0. The terms positive integers, non-negative integers, whole numbers, and counting numbers are also used. The set of the natural numbers is commonly denoted by a bold N or a blackboard bold ⁠⁠.",
            "tags": [
                "research",
                "web",
                "autonomous"
            ],
            "source": "self_researcher",
            "ts": 1779066214,
            "confidence": 0.825,
            "access_count": 0
        },
        {
            "key": "research:counting numbers:1779066214:1",
            "value": "In mathematics, the natural numbers are those used for counting and ordering. In common mathematical terminology, words colloquially used for counting are \"cardinal numbers\", and words used for ordering are \"ordinal numbers\". The natural numbers can, at times, appear as a convenient set of codes, that is, as what linguists call nominal numbers, forgoing many or all of the properties of being a number in a mathematical sense. Some definitions, including the standard ISO 80000-2, begin the natural numbers with 0, corresponding to the non-negative integers 0, 1, 2, 3,..., whereas others start with 1, corresponding to the positive integers 1, 2, 3,.....Texts that exclude zero from the natural numbers sometimes refer to the natural numbers together with zero as the whole numbers, while in other writings, that term is used instead for the integers.",
            "tags": [
                "research",
                "web",
                "autonomous"
            ],
            "source": "self_researcher",
            "ts": 1779066214,
            "confidence": 0.825,
            "access_count": 0
        },
        {
